     <int-org-section id="IO-UN.2424" sllink="SLSDOC" slsdocrf="INT-ORG-SECTREF">
          <heading>Organization</heading>
          <heading-note>April 2024</heading-note>
          <int-org-section id="IO-UN.2425" sllink="SLSDOC" slsdocrf="INT-ORG-SECTREF">
               <heading>Congress</heading>
               <p>The supreme body of the Union is the Universal Postal Congress, which normally meets every four years. It is responsible for the Constitution (the basic act of the Union), the General Regulations (which contain provisions relating to the application of the Constitution and the operation of the Union), changes in the provision of the Universal Postal Convention, approval of the strategic plan and budget parameters, formulation of overall policy on technical co-operation, and for elections and appointments. The 28th ordinary Congress was to be held in Dubai, United Arab Emirates, in 2025. A fourth extraordinary Congress was convened in October 2023, in Riyadh, Saudi Arabia.</p>
          </int-org-section>
          <int-org-section id="IO-UN.2427" sllink="SLSDOC" slsdocrf="INT-ORG-SECTREF">
               <heading>Council of Administration</heading>
               <p id="IO-UN.2428">
        The Council is composed of representatives of 41 member countries, elected by the Universal Postal Congress on the basis of an equitable geographical distribution. Meeting annually (2024: late April-early May), it is responsible for the affairs of the Union between Congresses, supervising the International Bureau and approving the Union’s budget. The Council also considers policies that may affect other sectors, such as standardization and quality of service, provides a forum for considering the implications of governmental policies with respect to competition, deregulation and trade-in-service issues for international postal services, and considers intergovernmental aspects of technical co-operation. The Council is responsible for promoting and co-ordinating all aspects of technical assistance among member countries. A Conference on Postal Regulation is convened during each session of the Council.
        <!--rotating chairmanship -->
               </p>
          </int-org-section>
          <int-org-section id="IO-UN.2429" sllink="SLSDOC" slsdocrf="INT-ORG-SECTREF">
               <heading>Postal Operations Council (POC)</heading>
               <p>As the technical organ of the UPU, the POC, which holds annual sessions and comprises 48 elected member countries, is responsible for the operational, economic and commercial aspects of international postal services, and supports the modernization of postal services and products. The POC has the authority to amend and enact the Detailed Regulations of the Universal Postal Convention, on the basis of decisions made at Congress. It promotes analysis undertaken by some postal services and the introduction of new postal products. It also prepares and issues recommendations concerning uniform standards of practice. On the recommendation of the 1999 Beijing Congress the POC established a Standards Board with responsibility for approving standards relating to telematics, postal technology and Electronic Data Interchange (EDI). Revised regulations on letter post and parcel international regulations entered into force on 1 January 2014. The following bodies report to the Postal Operations Council: the Direct Marketing Advisory Board (comprising representatives of designated national posts, private companies and industry associations); Express Mail Service (EMS) Cooperative (comprising, as at February 2024, 175 EMS designated operators covering most global EMS traffic; regulates the provision of a high-quality, competitive global EMS service); Telematics Cooperative (which, with voluntary participation by public, semi-public, and private postal operators, supports the use of new technologies in the improvement and expansion of postal services); Quality Service Fund (QSF) Board (which supports service improvements in developing member states); and the .POST Group (which steers the .POST top-level domain name).</p>
          </int-org-section>
          <int-org-section id="IO-UN.2430.1" sllink="SLSDOC" slsdocrf="INT-ORG-SECTREF">
               <heading>Consultative Committee</heading>
               <p>The Consultative Committee provides a platform for dialogue between postal industry stakeholders. Membership is open to non-governmental organizations representing customers, delivery service providers, workers' organizations, and suppliers of goods and services to the postal sector, as well as private companies with an interest in international postal services. All members are extended full observer status in all organs of the Union. The fourth extraordinary Congress that was held in October 2023 agreed to enhance participation of wider postal sector players (WPSPs—i.e. a broader spectrum of postal companies and partners, beyond government-designated postal operators) in the discussions and decision making of the Union, through the Consultative Committee. The Committee convenes annually, in Bern, to coincide with meetings of the Postal Operations Council.</p>
          </int-org-section>
          <int-org-section id="IO-UN.2431" sllink="SLSDOC" slsdocrf="INT-ORG-SECTREF">
               <heading>International Bureau </heading>
               <p>The International Bureau serves as an instrument of liaison, information and consultation for national postal administrations, and promotes technical co-operation among members. The Bureau comprises an Executive Office Directorate; other directorates on Policy, Regulation and Markets; Postal Operations; Development and Co-operation; Legal Affairs; Logistics; Human Resources; and Finance; and the Postal Technology Centre (the operational arm of the Telematics Cooperative). The Postal Technology Centre (supported by four Regional Support Centres) manages the following core activities: Post*Net, a global postal communication network, using EDI to provide monitoring services, a track-and-trace system, and postal remuneration and billing; the International Postal System, an integrated international mail management system, providing automated processing of dispatches and end-to-end tracking of items; and the International Financial System, a software application facilitating international money order services.</p>
