     <int-org-section id="IO-UN.2434" sllink="SLSDOC" slsdocrf="INT-ORG-SECTREF">
          <heading>Activities</heading>
          <p>The principles of the Union are to develop social, cultural and commercial communication through the efficient operation of the postal services; to guarantee freedom of transit and free circulation of postal items; to ensure the organization, development and modernization of postal services; to promote and participate in postal technical assistance between member countries; to ensure the interoperability of postal networks by implementing a suitable policy of standardization; to meet the changing needs of customers; and to improve the quality of service.</p>
          <p>
      In February 2024, as part of a celebration of the UPU’s 150th anniversary, the organization convened its inaugural international academic colloquium, addressing the theme `Achieving 
      <i>A Single Postal Territory</i>
      : A Global Promise—Past and Present’.
    </p>
          <p>World Post Day is celebrated each year on 9 October. A UPU World Leaders Forum and Parcel+Post Expo Conference are convened annually (2024: in Amsterdam, Netherlands, to follow on from World Post Day).</p>
          <p-group>
               <heading>Postal Vision 2030</heading>
               <p>In August 2021 the 27th ordinary Congress, convened in Abidjan, Côte d’Ivoire, endorsed the Abidjan Postal Strategy to guide the Union until the next Congress, and to support a new Postal Vision 2030. The Congress also adopted a new Integrated Remuneration Plan. The UPU’s Postal Vision 2030 is aimed at aligning the organization’s mission with the UN Sustainable Development Goals (SDGs). It has four key areas of action: (i) implementing focused policies and strengthening investment to reduce gaps in postal development, and advancing the use of postal networks to achieve socioeconomic development; (ii) harmonizing and enhancing postal regulatory frameworks; (iii) improving the performance of postal operators, including by means of diversification; and (iv) promoting the integration into the postal sector of public institutions and private sector stakeholders.</p>
          </p-group>
          <p-group>
               <heading>Abidjan Postal Strategy, 2021-25</heading>
               <p>The Abidjan Postal Strategy is focused on achieving the UPU’s Postal Vision 2030, and is based on the following three pillars: (i) strengthen the UPU’s mandate as the principal forum for postal sector development; (ii) reinforce the UPU’s role as a provider of innovative and affordable technical solutions for postal sector stakeholders; and (iii) enable the UPU to become the postal sector’s foremost information and knowledge centre.</p>
               <p>A UPU Strategy Summit was convened in October 2023, during the fourth extraordinary Congress (in Riyadh), to inform a successor Dubai Postal Strategy. This was to be approved in 2025 by the 28th ordinary Congress.</p>
          </p-group>
          <int-org-section id="UPU.IO.2" sllink="SLSDOC" slsdocrf="INT-ORG-SECTREF">
               <heading>Digital Services</heading>
               <p>The UPU promotes the use of digital technologies and innovative solutions in the postal sector, with a focus on research and development, capacity building, and the provision of technical assistance. The Union conducts market analysis to assist postal administrations in adapting to globalization and technological advances in world markets, and aims to reduce the digital divide between industrialized and developing nations. A Postal Data Hackathon event organized by the Union in June 2023 focused on analysis of the worldwide movement of goods through postal networks. The UPU sponsors the .POST top-level internet domain, which is authorized for exclusive use by the postal sector. Under the UPU Cybersecurity Framework several policy recommendations have been approved to enable member countries to build their capabilities to strengthen the security and resilience of digitalized postal processes and services. The UPU Secure E-services Framework comprises tools and legal instruments that facilitate the interconnection of national postal services. Through its Connect.post programme the Union aims to link all post offices worldwide to the internet by 2030. A UPU E-Commerce Programme (ECOMPRO) was initiated in 2014. The UPU is a founding member of the UN eTrade-for-all initiative, which aims to support participation by least developed countries in e-commerce. In May 2022 the UPU and WCO signed a co-operation accord that provided for enhanced co-operation in developing e-commerce and postal network security. A UPU Multilateral Data Sharing Agreement (MDSA) was adopted in April 2021 by the Postal Technology Centre. By 2024 the Union had issued digital capability recommendation reports based on assessments conducted in 10 developing countries.</p>
          </int-org-section>
          <int-org-section id="UPU.IO.3" sllink="SLSDOC" slsdocrf="INT-ORG-SECTREF">
               <heading>Physical Services</heading>
               <p>The UPU has observed that, while the volume of traditional letter mail has declined in recent years, small parcel deliveries have been boosted by e-commerce. The UPU’s Global Monitoring System (GMS) measures postal performance through the GMS Statistical System for Analysis and Reports (GMS STAR). The Union’s International Bureau undertakes quality tests on postal products and services worldwide, monitoring international links through the use of test letters and parcels; the Bureau also publishes end-to-end delivery standards. Consultants are sent to selected countries to promote the implementation of improvements in quality of service. The UPU works to advance the global address infrastructure by supporting the development of national addressing and postcode systems and by helping to advance the international interoperability of name and address data. The Union fosters postal supply chain integration. An Integrated Product Plan approved in September 2018 by the second UPU extraordinary Congress aims to develop an integrated portfolio of physical (letter, parcel and EMS) postal products.</p>
               <p>The UPU sets the rates of remuneration for cross-border postal deliveries. In September 2019 the third extraordinary Congress concluded a unanimous agreement on a new postal renumerations rate regime, which included an option of self-declared rates—in effect since 1 July 2020—for countries where inbound letter and small parcel post volume exceeds 75,000 metric tons. (The USA had previously advised the organization that it intended to withdraw its membership if this issue was not promptly addressed.) In September 2021 the 27th Congress adopted a new Integrated Remuneration System that aimed to integrate the UPU’s `terminal dues’ renumeration system (initiated in 1969), inward land rates, ECOMPRO rates, and EMS rates. The UPU issues a yearly compendium of transit charges, for intermediate third-party designated operators that forward postal items to a destination country.</p>
               <p>
        The UPU develops regulations, processes and best practices to facilitate efficient movement through the cross-border postal supply chain, with a focus on security, transport and customs. The UPU’s Postal Security Group is tasked with developing security strategies at the global and regional levels with the aim of preventing mail-related fraud, theft and misuse. In March 2007 the UPU and the 
        <xr pageref="N" ref="WB0231XM.IO.TXT.16">International Air Transport Association</xr>
         signed a Memorandum of Understanding (MOU) on developing and harmonizing standards and increasing the use of technologies (such as bar coding, radio frequency identification, and the processing of electronic data) to improve air mail flows. A UPU-
        
        International Civil Aviation Organization 
        <xr pageref="N" ref="IO-UN.2009">(ICAO)</xr>
         Contact Committee, enhancing the partnership between both organizations, was established in 2018. The UPU and the 
        <xr pageref="N" ref="WB0231XM.IO.TXT.15">Intergovernmental Organization for International Carriage by Rail</xr>
         concluded an MOU in January 2018 that aimed to facilitate co-operation on the transport of postal items by rail. A UPU-WCO Contact Committee works to elaborate processes that facilitate the swift clearance of postal items through customs. An advance digital Customs Declaration System was developed by the UPU’s Postal Technology Centre.
      </p>
          </int-org-section>
          <int-org-section id="IO-UN.UPU.0001" sllink="SLSDOC" slsdocrf="INT-ORG-SECTREF">
               <heading>Financial Services</heading>
               <p>
        An electronic UPU clearing system (UPU*Clearing) became operational in 2003, for the settlement of international postal accounts. The 2008 Congress adopted an optional Postal Payment Services (PPS) Agreement and its Regulations, which aimed to enable postal operators to operate faster, more secure and more accessible electronic money transfer services to communities without access to banks or other formal money transfer networks. A PPS*Clearing system and PPS User Group have been established. In October 2023 the fourth extraordinary Congress agreed reforms to the PPS system, in particular to facilitate broader engagement with WPSPs. UPU supports the use by member states of the trademarked PosTransfer system, to facilitate the real-time exchange of international electronic money transfers. The UPU’s Postal Economics Programme conducts economic research aimed at analysing the uneven postal sector development of developing countries and providing growth models for their postal sectors. Focus has been given to expanding the role of national postal administrations in such countries in supporting the use of e-commerce activities by micro and small enterprises. Through its Financial Inclusion Technical Assistance Facility (FITAF) the UPU supports projects providing digital financial services support to impoverished and `unbanked’ people (i.e. excluded from mainstream financial institutions) in Africa, Asia and the Pacific. A Japan Fund for Postal Financial Inclusion was initiated in mid-2020 to support UPU initiatives aimed at promoting financial inclusion in developing countries. In April 2022 the UPU issued 
        <publ-name>Blockchains for a Sustainable Postal Future,</publ-name>
         which addressed the onwards use of blockchain and distributed ledger technologies (DLTS—systems that enable simultaneous record updating across multiple access points), with a focus on advancing inclusive financial services and logistics.
      </p>
          </int-org-section>
          <int-org-section id="UPU.IO.SD.1" sllink="SLSDOC" slsdocrf="INT-ORG-SECTREF">
               <heading>Sustainable Development</heading>
               <p>The UPU monitors the postal sector's contribution to the SDGs. In November 2019 a project aimed at advancing postal social services was initiated. The UPU promotes environmental sustainability in the postal sector, encouraging recycling programmes and the use of environmentally friendly products and resources. The organization maintains an online tool— the Online Solution for Carbon Analysis and Reporting (OSCAR)—which measures the carbon footprint of postal operations. In October 2023 the Union’s fourth extraordinary Congress endorsed a `Green Package’ that included targets to reduce greenhouse gas emissions within the postal sector, and the establishment of a voluntarily-funded Climate Facility to support mitigation and adaptation activities. A global disaster risk reduction and management policy for the postal sector is under development.</p>
          </int-org-section>
          <int-org-section id="IO-UN.UPU.0002" sllink="SLSDOC" slsdocrf="INT-ORG-SECTREF">
               <heading>Technical Co-operation and Capacity Building</heading>
               <p>The UPU's Integrated Postal Reform and Development Plan aims to ensure that the state obligation to provide the UPS is met, and that the conditions required to modern­ize the postal sector are established, with a view to benefiting both individual citizens and businesses. Through its programme on development co-operation the UPU provides postal technical assistance to developing member countries. The UPU has undertaken projects to develop human resources in the postal sector. It has developed guides, training materials and training models through its Trainpost distance-learning programme, and organizes capacity-building training workshops in developing countries and on a regional basis.</p>
               <p>
        The 2022 
        <publ-name>Postal Development Report,</publ-name>
         issued in October of that year, included an updated composite Integrated Index for Postal Development that measured the reliability, reach, relevance and resilience of postal services in 172 countries. The report outlined 10 levels of postal development and excellence: the top tier comprised the postal services of Austria, the People’s Republic of China, France, Germany, Japan and Switzerland, with the postal services of Cameroon, Colombia and Saudi Arabia leading their respective regions.
      </p>
               <p>The inaugural UPU TradePost Forum was convened in December 2023, in Geneva, with a focus on promoting trade inclusion; the first TradePost Awards were given at that time.</p>
               <p>A UPU Emergency and Solidarity Fund (ESF), which became operational in November 2011, facilitates the recovery of basic postal services in countries affected by natural or technological disasters and armed conflict. In May 2022 the Council of Administration decided to create a new working group to identify member states in need, to develop a humanitarian assistance mechanism, and to define sources of emergency funding.</p>
               <p usage="edio">In May 2022 the Council of Administration adopted a resolution that urged support to rebuild Ukraine’s war-affected postal infrastructure, and tasked the UPU Secretariat with monitoring the requirements of that country’s national postal service, Ukrposhta, and with assessing impacts of the ongoing war on the UPU’s activities and on the wider global postal network.</p>
               <!--Ukraine situation in the EERCA version-->
          </int-org-section>
          <int-org-section id="UPU.IO.PHIL.1" sllink="SLSDOC" slsdocrf="INT-ORG-SECTREF">
               <heading>Philately and International Reply Coupons (IRCs)</heading>
               <p>The UPU’s Philately and IRC programme acts as the secretariat of the World Association for the Development of Philately (WADP), organizes the WADP Numbering System (which records all official legally issued stamps), manages the International Bureau’s universal postage stamp collection, and administers the IRC scheme. In 2023 the Postal Operations Council approved the first taxonomy defining types of digital philatelic products.</p>
               <!--crypto stamps; so-called non-fungible token (NFT) stamps - collectibles-->
               <p usage="edio">In May 2021—in view of a non-binding Advisory Opinion issued in February 2019 by the International Court of Justice (ICJ), which had found that the United Kingdom was illegally occupying the Chagos Archipielago (constituted since 1965 as the British Indian Ocean Territory), and should return the islands forthwith to Mauritius—the Council of Administration recommended that UPU member states should no longer register, distribute or forward postage stamps issued by the territory. The decision was endorsed by the 27th Universal Postal Congress in August 2021.</p>
               <!--Chagos dispute in ASS version-->
          </int-org-section>
     </int-org-section>
     <int-org-section id="IO-UN.2439" sllink="SLSDOC" slsdocrf="INT-ORG-SECTREF">
          <heading>Finance</heading>
          <p>All of the UPU's regular budget expenses are financed by member countries, based on a contribution class system. The UPU's annual regular budget for 2023 was projected at 38.9m. Swiss francs.</p>
          <p usage="edio">In September 2018 the the UPU’s second extraordinary Congress approved a reduction in the UPU contributions to be received by economically disadvantaged small island developing states. A Least Developed Countries Special Account was authorized by the 27th Congress, meeting in Abidjan in August 2021.</p>
     </int-org-section>
